  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1584270532" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1584270532" />
    <a title="D.L. Howe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11485401-d-l-howe"><img alt="D.L. Howe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1636885945p2/11485401.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1584270532?book_show_action=true">May 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="D.L. Howe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="D.L. Howe" href="/user/show/11485401-d-l-howe">D.L. Howe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/11335538-forbidden">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11485401-d-l-howe?shelf=taboo">taboo</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1584270532" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15461905501562591433">It took me a week to get my emotions in check when it comes to this. I upped my rating because I can finally look past the pain it inflicted and see the beauty, no matter how broken. <br/><br/>This is less of a review and more of me slowly but surely falling apart ...<br/><br/>It seems everyone wants to compare this to Hale. I don’t know if Kristi set out to write a book that embodied this one, but I do know that Suzuma was inspired by Flowers in the Attic. Which for me personally is where my fascination with this </span>
  <span id="freeText15461905501562591433" style="display:none">It took me a week to get my emotions in check when it comes to this. I upped my rating because I can finally look past the pain it inflicted and see the beauty, no matter how broken. <br /><br />This is less of a review and more of me slowly but surely falling apart ...<br /><br />It seems everyone wants to compare this to Hale. I don’t know if Kristi set out to write a book that embodied this one, but I do know that Suzuma was inspired by Flowers in the Attic. Which for me personally is where my fascination with this taboo subject began. For me personally comparing Forbidden with Hale is like comparing apples and oranges. The only thing they share is the taboo love between a brother and sister. To me that’s where the comparison ends. So, if that’s the case how about we just compare both books to Flowers in the Attic? <br /><br />I’ve only been introduced to the mother in half a page and I already want to stab her eyes out. Honestly nothing pisses me off more than siblings taking care of each other while the parents do nothing. You made the choice to have them now do your fucking job!<br /><br />I could seriously rhapsodize how disgusting and awful this woman is. She should’ve been sterilized. <br /><br />Seriously I’ve read books that elicit strong emotions in me but this one takes the cake. <br /><br />Goddam them all (except Maya) I just want to wrap him in my arms and promise him that everything will get better. God, I hate this! <br /><br />Kit is such a little shit! I almost despise him as much as the mother!<br /><br />Maybe knowing how this ends will eventually desensitize me. One can only hope but I doubt it. On the other hand it’s hard to enjoy anything good (even if the good seems far and few between) while I’m waiting for the other shoe to drop. <br /><br />I’m really having a hard time understanding the draw of this one. Even without knowing what’s to come, it’s still the most depressing book I’ve ever read and I’ve read The Bell Jar.<br /><br />There’s just no fucking relief! Where are the shining moments of beauty? I’d even settle for a sarcastic joke. The pain just becomes dulled until you’re hit over the head with some other form of devastation<br /><br />Have you ever seen Claire Danes ugly cry with the quivering chin? Yeah I’ve never done that before ... until now. <br /><br />I can definitely see the similarities between this and Flowers in the Attic. Especially in the relationship between the mother and the younger children. <br /><br />When they finally come together, it was the most raw, realistic scene I’ve ever read. That in itself is beautiful.<br /><br />In the end I’m giving this a high rating not because I enjoyed it but because it’s good. The writing alone is enough, the relationship building is phenomenal. If it wasn’t well done it would never elicit the amount of emotions that it tore straight from the depth of my soul. Goddam you Tabitha Suzuma!</span>
  <a data-text-id="15461905501562591433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


